### [Psalms Chapter 143](../../../bib/kjv/psa143.htm#001.md)

[Psalms 143:1](../../../bib/kjv/psa143.htm#001.md)

<span class="margnote"><span id="an_001">psa 143:1</span></span>

In structure and style, like the preceding (Psalms 104-142), this Psalm
is clearly evinced to be David's. It is a prayer for pardon, and for
relief from enemies; afflictions, as usual, producing confession and
penitence. ([Psa 143:1-12](../../../bib/kjv/psa143.htm#001).md)

in thy faithfulness . . . and . . . righteousness--or, God's regard to
the claims which He has permitted His people to make in His covenant.

[Psalms 143:2](../../../bib/kjv/psa143.htm#002.md)

<span class="margnote"><span id="an_002">psa 143:2</span></span>

enter . . . judgment--deal not in strict justice.

shall no . . . justified--or, "is no man justified," or "innocent" ([Job
14:3](../../../bib/kjv/job014.htm#003.md); [Rom
3:20](../../../bib/kjv/rom003.htm#020).md).

[Psalms 143:3](../../../bib/kjv/psa143.htm#003.md)

<span class="margnote"><span id="an_003">psa 143:3</span></span>

The exciting reason for his prayer--his afflictions--led to confession
as just made: he now makes the complaint.

as those that have been long dead--deprived of life's comforts (compare
[Psa 40:15](../../../bib/kjv/psa040.htm#015.md); [Psa
88:3-6](../../../bib/kjv/psa088.htm#003).md).

[Psalms 143:5](../../../bib/kjv/psa143.htm#005.md)

<span class="margnote"><span id="an_005">psa 143:5</span></span>

The distress is aggravated by the contrast of former comfort ([Psa
22:3-5](../../../bib/kjv/psa022.htm#003).md), for whose return he longs.

a thirsty land--which needs rain, as did his spirit God's gracious
visits ([Psa 28:1](../../../bib/kjv/psa028.htm#001.md); [Psa
89:17](../../../bib/kjv/psa089.htm#017).md).

[Psalms 143:7](../../../bib/kjv/psa143.htm#007.md)

<span class="margnote"><span id="an_007">psa 143:7</span></span>

spirit faileth--is exhausted.

[Psalms 143:8](../../../bib/kjv/psa143.htm#008.md)

<span class="margnote"><span id="an_008">psa 143:8</span></span>

(Compare [Psa 25:1-4](../../../bib/kjv/psa025.htm#001.md); [Psa
59:16](../../../bib/kjv/psa059.htm#016).md).

the way . . . walk--that is, the way of safety and righteousness ([Psa
142:3-6](../../../bib/kjv/psa142.htm#003).md).

[Psalms 143:9](../../../bib/kjv/psa143.htm#009.md)

<span class="margnote"><span id="an_009">psa 143:9</span></span>

(Compare [Psa 31:15-20](../../../bib/kjv/psa031.htm#015).md).

[Psalms 143:10](../../../bib/kjv/psa143.htm#010.md)

<span class="margnote"><span id="an_010">psa 143:10</span></span>

(Compare [Psa 5:8](../../../bib/kjv/psa005.htm#008.md); [Psa
27:11](../../../bib/kjv/psa027.htm#011).md).

land of uprightness--literally, "an even land" ([Psa
26:12](../../../bib/kjv/psa026.htm#012).md).

[Psalms 143:11](../../../bib/kjv/psa143.htm#011.md)

<span class="margnote"><span id="an_011">psa 143:11</span></span>

(Compare [Psa 23:3](../../../bib/kjv/psa023.htm#003.md); [Psa
119:156](../../../bib/kjv/psa119.htm#156).md).

[Psalms 143:12](../../../bib/kjv/psa143.htm#012.md)

<span class="margnote"><span id="an_012">psa 143:12</span></span>

God's mercy to His people is often wrath to His and their enemies
(compare [Psa 31:17](../../../bib/kjv/psa031.htm#017).md).

thy servant--as chosen to be such, entitled to divine regard.

